,Recommended,265890,29551432,Posted: 28 January,all,_BillCipher | ScrapTF,"In Short -A couple weeks ago I had a couple £ in my Steam wallet and was not sure what to buy. A friend pointed me to a small puzzle game calledHexcells. I was sceptical, but after buying & downloading it, I am glad I took the plunge. Not dissimilar to the old Windows game Minesweeper, Hexcells is a little Indie game created by a man by the name of Matthew Brown. There are two other Hexcells games, Hexcells Plus and Hexcells Infinite.In Depth -It is not easy to explain Hexcells' concept in a review; you mainly learn as you go on. Through the later levels, you are taught extra rules and slowly the puzzles increase in difficulty. If you enjoy logical puzzles, you'll have a blast with Hexcells. No aspect of this game requires luck or guessing, every puzzle can be solved using your mind. Too easy for you? Keep going, the later puzzles are not only giant but also pretty darn hard. Of course, multiple people have created guides showing what to do in each if you want to cheat your way through, but that takes the fun out of it! In all, Hexcells is a calming puzzle experience that is perfect when you just want to chill out.PROs and CONs -PROs -A simple concept that gets expanded and twisted in later levels.The soundtrack is ambient and calming.Enough levels to give you a decent amount of game time for the money spent.CONs -A few times in which the gameplay gets repetitive. There is a little too much time between new mechanics being shown.Very little instruction when the game starts. I had literally no clue what I was doing at first. It took me a while...Not very simple to pick up and play. You have to relearn all the symbols the game teaches you once. Something that could be fixed with an 'instructions' section of the menu or even titlescreen.FinallyThere are tons of Indie puzzle games on Steam. Some succeed. Some fail. Some are absolutely horrible. Some are actually great. And Hexcells absolutely nails it. I love nearly everything about Hexcells. Thank you, Matthew Brown for making such a chill puzzle game that really hits the spot when I'm bored.Enjoy this review? Did it help you choose whether to buy the game or not?Join my group,Cipher's Take Onfor more reviews, and share your own too!~ _BillCipher"
,Recommended,265890,17230440,"Posted: 25 July, 2015",all,Weasel,"I'm something of a Picross nut, having played and near-beaten most of Nintendo's Picross games. When I saw Hexcells on the Steam New Releases section, I was quite happy; I have always thought these kinds of logic puzzles were better on a platform with a mouse. A few bucks later (thanks to Steam trading card sales - this game doesn't give out cards, btw), I had Hexcells in my library.The actual logic of Hexcells is not difficult to grasp. If you've played Minesweeper or Picross 3D, you'll be right at home. You'll be following numbers inside of hexes, with symbols indicating whether the surrounding blue hexes will be consecutive or split, and later you will find numbers on rows or columns as well, with similar symbols. These symbols are, admittedly, not as easy to remember as I'd like (a problem that even Picross 3D had). I've made a few mistakes in puzzles because I misread the symbol in a given hex. In a related note, it's also somewhat easy to forget which mouse button performs which function, causing stupid mistakes that get recorded in your level score. Hexcells does not have a time limit of any kind, so you are essentially free to brute-force your way through a puzzle if you so desire, but making mistakes reduces how many hexes you receive as a reward for that level, and Steam Achievement nuts will probably want to avoid doing that if possible, as there is an achievement awarded for getting a perfect score on every level.Presentationally speaking, Hexcells is simple and pleasing. The visuals are extremely minimalist (hexagons, and only hexagons); the only visual effects you'll be seeing are the tiny animations for shading or breaking hexes. The music is electronic ambience, in the style of Solar Fields (i.e. Mirror's Edge or Capsized), with the added effect that in-game sound effects are played on rhythm, a la Lumines or Rez. If I could complain about the presentation in any area, though, Hexcells does not provide a color-blind option (though I am not color-blind, I am unsure if the game's use of blue and orange would cause problems for those who are), and the low-contrast nature of the backgrounds makes the ""Menu"" button difficult to find.I am pleased to report that Hexcells performs admirably on both Windows and Linux, owing to its nature as a Unity game. I would presume that Macintosh support is also good, as a result. Both of my test machines (no slouches, admittedly) ran the game with no obvious slowdowns or graphical glitches. I'd wager most machines made in the last half-decade will work just fine; I suppose netbooks may be feasible as well, but as I do not have access to one right now, I cannot say for certain, so Your Mileage May Vary.About the biggest complaint I have about Hexcells, though, is that there are just not enough puzzles. Hexcells offers 6 ""worlds,"" with five puzzles each, and the last puzzle essentially acting as a credits reel. I finished the game in a little over an hour, though I have not achieved Perfect on every puzzle just yet.All that said, though, at $3 or less, Hexcells is certainly not a waste of your money. I'd like to see more logic-puzzle games like this on Steam."
76561198024972696,Recommended,265890,33018388,Posted: 29 June,all,DALCOhstangultion,"""Hexcells"" is a very well done, fun little game.  As everyone has said, it's like Minesweeper with hexes instead of squares.  The learning curve is perfectly done, and even I (who maybe played a handful of Minesweeper games several decades ago) completed it without problem.  I've got only a few quibbles:- The game is short.  Its 30 puzzles took me 4.1 hours to complete, and I'm SLOW at this.  Still, I paid less than a dollar for it during the Steam Summer Sale, so it was worth it.  Heck, even by my el-cheapo ""dollar an hour"" metric for games, it's worth it at its current list price of about three dollars.  Still, It would be nice if it were longer.- Even though the game is playable under Steam's Family Sharing capability, it doesn't handle its Achievements well in that.  Anyone who shares your game gets all the Achievements you got when you played it.- The main menu in the game has 3 ""slots.""  Initially, I thought they were for different clumps of puzzles.  Instead, it turns out those are just a poor man's set of profiles.  The puzzles inside the slots are identical to each other.- The white space between hexes in the puzzles isn't really explained well.  It turns out that when counting neighbors of hexes, the white space is important:  the stuff across it doesn't count.  But, when looking for contigous or non-contiguose hexes in rows or diagonals, the white space gets ignored.All of the above are just minor nits.  So, I'm happy to recommend the game."
