76561198067227433,Recommended,265890,32860447,Posted: 27 June,all,courtepattes,"An excellent puzzle game, reminiscent of the old Minesweeper game on Windows, only much better.Pros:+ Polished and relaxing interface. The game is nice to look at, and as you will stare intently at your screen to find the solution, this is not to be dismissed.+ Ambient sounds are perfect.+ Interesting and evolving gameplay.+? Easy achievements.Cons:- May lack challenge.- Very short (I perfected the game in less than two hours so I could have got a refund).- Little replay value.- Some rules are unclear (adjacency in discontinuous rows and columns especially).- The rules are only explained in the level where they appear for the first time. A reminder of all rules would have been helpful.Verdict: Highly recommended. Cheap and smooth, nice and relaxing, fun and a little challenging, this makes a perfect addition in your puzzle games library. Two sequels, increasingly more challenging, are available on Steam.Comments and developments:In this game you must find the 'bombs' hidden on some pattern made of adjacent hexagons. Just as in Minesweeper, hexagons tell you how many bombs are to be found in the neighboring cells. As the game goes on, new mechanics are added: how many bombs there are in row and columns, whether the bomb are adjacent are not. Only by combining all the clues can the bombs be all found.It must be stressed that the levels are not random. Hence, they have been carefully crafted and there is a logical way to go through. Unlike Minesweeper, you will never start by randomly clicking and if you are stuck, it's only because you missed a clue or did not figure out how to combine them adequately. All levels can be achieved with no mistake.Also, a very good thing: the first mistake doesn't count and you can still get a perfect score. However, if you commit a second one, the first mistake will also be counted as such. As clicking errors happen, this little safeguard is a real blessing."
,Recommended,265890,27476755,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,SirMarth01,"Hexcells is essentially an overall enhancement of Minesweeper. Where Minesweeper has mines, you have blue hexagons. Where Minesweeper has randomly generated puzzles that sometimes force you to guess, Hexcells has predesigned puzzles that always give you enough information to solve it without ever needing to guess. (Although sometimes it may feel otherwise.)Why go for Hexcells over Minesweeper when there's a limited set of puzzles? Hexcells' puzzles areincrediblywell designed, starting simple and adding new mechanics as you move along. Beyond just telling you how many hexes nearby are blue, you get information on if they're all connected or not. Vertical or diagonal columns get similar treatment. Sometimes blue hexes have numbers in them, telling you how many blue hexes are in the surrounding area.Eventually, you have to combine these hints in creative ways to determine where the blue hexes are—or where they aren't. When you're finally able to combine them all to work your way to completion, it provides a level of satisfaction that Minesweeper just can't compete with.The only real downside to Hexcells is that it's pretty short—an acceptable downside, considering the price. Thankfully, Hexcells Plus (more puzzles) and Hexcells Infinite (more puzzles, a random puzzle generator,andplayer-created levels) are available, and getting the complete pack is incredibly affordable (and highly recommended), especially on sale."
