,Recommended,265890,33842721,Posted: 27 July,all,100% Hippo,"Hexcells is a terrific, relaxing puzzle game. It takes place on a hex-based grid, and the point of each level is to figure out which cells to mark and which to not, similar to the premise of Minesweeper, but in the best possible way. There are several different mechanics introduced throughout the game, and each is introduced well and used in interesting ways in the following levels. There are 30 total levels, and some are short, mainly for the purpose of introducing a concept, but some, particularly the later levels, can take quite a while. I don't remember how long it took me the first time, but I've played through a few times to get to my current playtime.It is nice that there is a unique solution to each level, and guessing is never required. You can always progress purely through logic, it just may take a bit to see how. There's no time constraint involved at all, so there's no reason not to take your time and work carefully through the levels. I found that almost all the mistakes I made were when I went too fast and hit the wrong button. The soundtrack is ambient and very relaxing, and the game does a good job of making the sound effects for actions in the game go with the music too.The achievements come from progressing through the game, and from perfecting every level. The game's definition of 'perfecting' a level is nice and generous, and you can make a single mistake and it still counts, which comes in handy in some of the larger levels where at least one mistake is fairly inevitable. The achievements aren't too hard to get, though you may need to retry a level of two to minimize your mistakes.Overall this is a wonderful, relaxing, puzzle game, and while it is somewhat on the short side, if you like it you should definitely get the other two, Hexcells Plus, and Hexcells Infinite. They're all wonderful, and Infinite even comes with a level generator."
