,Recommended,265890,20065771,"Posted: 29 December, 2015",all,spectre51,"Logic puzzle game, similar to minesweeper but without the need to guess any moves.I really enjoyed playing through Hexcells while short. Every puzzle (30 to complete) in it is fully solvable using logic, no guessing is required. It gradually introduces you to different clues as it increases in difficulty as you progress through the levels.It is forgiving there is not punishment to making mistakes or guessing other than being unable to “perfect” the level which is completing it with a limited amount of mistakes, which is also the only real reason to reply levels.One negative is that puzzles can’t be saved mid game, so you lose progress when you exit.Even though it can be quite quick to get through the 30 available puzzles I still recommend Hexcells as; one on sale it is very cheap, and two it’s a good starting point to ease you into the series.I had no technical issues with Hexcells."
,Recommended,265890,20120411,"Posted: 30 December, 2015",all,Hyperion,"This game is simply great. If you are one of those cool people who pass their idle time on their PC by playing the classic minesweeper game, Hexcells takes that to a whole new level.Things I like about the game:+ I bought all the three games (not costly at all) and it is absolutely fun.+ The levels are totally solvable by logic and you wont face a guessing situation like you would in classic minesweeper game. This requires a lot more logical reasoning than minesweeper and I really loved it.+ This game has its own ambient music (which some of you may like).+ The display is clean and the game gives proper introduction on every new rule as they appear.+ The game runs equally smoothly on Linux, Windows and Mac. So I am able to play on different machines at work, or home.+ Very small installation size, Downloads the game in a new machine instantly.+ This game even has steam achievements.Things I did not like about the game:- No profile synchronization among devices. Everytime you install this in a new machine, you have to start from the beginning.- Music could be a bit more mild, I did not like short length repeatative music, had it turned off within first few levels.- Levels do not change, you can make mistakes and repeat the level with 0 mistake. Although if you challenge yourself honestly, this is not much of a problem (In the Infinity version, there are random levels though).- I am not sure about the scoring system. How making mistake affects your score and if there is any relation with time etc.- Short gameplay duration (this wont take you very long to complete, but I personally wont mind replaying).So far, I like the game and would recommend to anyone who is into these type of tiny games."
