,Recommended,265890,22528217,"Posted: 19 April, 2016",all,愛 ♥Imouto-chan♥,"Hexcells proves that puzzle games don't need to be extremely complex to thoroughly enjoy.Now if you've ever played Minesweeper then right away you'll realise the basic premise is the same in both games. You click on a hexagon and it'll reveal a number and that number is how many 'mines' are around that specific hexagon, sound familiar? What Hexcells adds onto the original Minesweeper experience is a more puzzle oriented design to its levels, with each progressively testing your knowledge of new mechanics that get introduced throughout the worlds. That beind said each level in a world has a set amount of 'mines' in predefined locations, some puzzles might take you multiple tries to first realise the pattern but once you do it's abundantly satisfying when you finally solve it.This game has a very minimalistic approach to both its audio and graphics; there isn't much to complain about because it gets the job done. Simple hexagon shapes with an electronic ambience in the style of Solar Fields, with the added bonus of the game's audio playing in rhythm to your actions.Honestly my biggest complaint with this game is that there aren't enough puzzles, if you're like me than it'll leave you with that feeling of ""I want more!"". Thankfully though this game is really cheap, I'd highly recommend a purchase to anyone interested in either puzzles or games like Minesweeper/Sudoku/Picross."
