,Not Recommended,265890,19322729,"Posted: 27 November, 2015",all,TheTrueParadoxe,"I really don't understand the appeal.In this game, like minesweeper, you have to find the 'mines' with the number of adjacent mines of one tile. The difference are that few levels of Hexcell aren't randomly generated and more complex mechanics are introduced as you go on.The first problem I have with this game is that it does not let you fail. Rather than failing a level for hitting a 'mine', it only count your mistake. It sound like a good thing, but it simply inadvertently spoils the game. I admit that I don't know what could be done to fix this, but nevertheless its the equivalent to trying to solve a math problem with the answer in front of you. You might do your best not to look, you still end up figuring something that you wouldn't have normally.The second problem is related to the few inconsistencies of the game. It's a minor issue, but sometimes, it seems that the game take liberties with its own rules (or simply doesn't set them). For example;Two mines in a row of four tiles are said to be next to each other? Turn out that 'next to each other' still count when the row is separated by a huge white space.symbols like '--' indicate that mines aren't next to each other? It only mean that at least one mine is not connected to the others.etc.Like a said, this is a minor issue, but combined with a very short unpunishing game, it doesn't leave you anything worthwhile. I can't recommend this game when other interesting puzzle games are available for the same price."
