76561198074867492,Recommended,265890,30082007,Posted: 21 February,all,Dragon Force,"TheHexcellsseries can be looked at as a modernized version of the classicMinesweeper. The simplistic design allows the player to focus purely on the puzzle. The contrast between the hexes are clearly visible thanks to the usage of bright yellow and blue colors. The sound design in the game is as serene as it's sublime. Again, the focus of the player is directed to the gameplay and not on the ambient sounds, which do somewhat calm the mind. Of course, the goal of the game is to complete the puzzles with as less mistakes as possible.Very close to coffee break puzzling perfection. You can spend anywhere from ten minutes to a lifetime playing and still feel like your brain is being tested. Highly recommended if you likedMinesweeper. Basically,Hexcellsis whatMinesweepershould have been."
76561197989273094,Recommended,265890,30165643,Posted: 25 February,all,War,"A very successful evolution of the classic ""minesweeper""--Darwin would be proud.There is very little need to ""guess"" as to spot selections, puzzles evolve/progress with new options/features at a very sound pace. There is significant variety in puzzles and this keeps the game enjoyable and fresh through the initial playthrough. However, Hexcells is NOT proceduarlly generated. As such, once you have played through the title you will need to shelve it for an extended period in order to have any viable replay value.Although I own the other two installments in this franchise I have yet to play them. I hope that they, or a future 4th installment, will have some procedural generation options to afford a significant boost to replay value.Overall, a fun, albeit very short, title which is well worth your money--especially if found on sale."
