,Not Recommended,265890,11047015,"Posted: 3 July, 2014",all,Ooops,"Hexcells is basically a collection of puzzles, the kinds of which are a dime a dozen in GAMES magazine or Dell's puzzle magazines.This particular kind starts like hexagonal minsweeper, then adds new kinds of clues that aren't unlike Picross. The visuals are minimal, but pleasing and the ambient music mixes well with the sounds generated by your progression towards the solutions.The BIG problem is that it's way too short and easy. None of the 29 puzzles presented any kind of challenge to me, and we all know that I'm no Puzzle got (Remember my Spacechem debacle). I was really taken aback when I discovered the ""1"", ""2"", ""3"" entries in the menu didn't bring me to different puzzles but were just save slots. I couldn't believe it was that short. The puzzles may be handcrafted, ensuring that there never is need for guessing, but they aren't all that elegant for it. Not only are the puzzles easy, but they also contain way too many redundant clues.Another minor problem is that, by default, the mouse buttons used to open a cell or indicate it's part of the pattern are reversed from Minesweeper, which caused a couple of mistakes from my part.Now, I've already begun playing the sequel, Hexcells Plus and the puzzles there aere much more challenging, which is a good thing.Anyone with a certain level of puzzle exprience should probably skip this one and go straight to Hexcells Plus."
