,Recommended,265890,19342848,"Posted: 28 November, 2015",all,Kobold Commando,"The best way I can think of to describe Hexcells is not as a puzzle game, but as a ""meditation game"" and a sort of mental massage.The gameplay follows on from Minesweeper, you start with the same rules, identifying blue hexes by the non-blue hexes telling you the number of adjacent blues.  But new mechanics are introduced which pushes it toward the realm of Sudoku.  I never found it frustrating or confounding, because the rules are simple enough that you only have to look for the next step, not make crazy leaps of logic.  Also, while you don't get a full score for making several mistakes, each mistake you make at the same time serves as a hint and moves you closer to the solution (a nice parallel with positivity in real life!)So the gameplay requires you to be active and logical mentally, but not so much that you can't relax or have to get stressed.  And the rest of the game with its simple visuals and procedural ambient soundtrack works to make one of the most relaxing experiences I've seen in games.  The puzzles and music are in a nice area between idleness and frustrating which lets you slip easily into a meditative state while playing.I highly recommend this game, especially if you turn off the TV, turn the lights down a bit, kick up your feet, turn on a humidifier, lay a damp washcloth on your forehead, and just completely relax while playing.  For anyone dealing with excessive levels of stress or anxiety, this game could be outright therapeutic!"
,Recommended,265890,19310702,"Posted: 27 November, 2015",all,Droidge,"The board is almost solved with no mistakes so far. With numbers and blue cells everywhere, all that is left is two yellow cells. It's unclear what cell's to be cleared, and what cell is to be marked. You look at the board, squinting your eyes as you make hypotheses about what would happen if either cell was marked.And then, when you're as confident as an eagle swooping down for prey, you slowly but steadily bring your mouse cursor to the cell you chose. You're sure you can't be wrong; after all, you thought it all out. The numbers all add up. It's a calculated move. This cell just can't have a number below it.And as the cursor finally lands on top of the cell, you click with your mouse.But it turns out you pressed RMB.11/10. Super Meat Boy for intellectuals."
