,Recommended,265890,11983059,"Posted: 4 September, 2014",all,grzhan,"TL;DR - minesweeper, short, needs polishing, nice for 1$This puzzle game is basically ""minesweeper"" in hex form. Yes, there are some additions. Yes, the levels have ""shapes"". But it's basically ""minesweeper"".It's not too hard - took me just over an hour to finish. It's kind of fun for those who like this sort of thing.However, it's not polished enough:- The controls are confusing (right-click ""opens"" the cell, left click sets the ""mine"" - the opposite of minesweeper) so that most of the mistakes I made were from mixing up the buttons- whenever you move the mouse over a hex, it ""reacts"" similar to a wrong click. That is very confusing when you play ""fast"", as you get the ""you did wrong"" feedback all the time making you hesitate- The ""extra"" information (""the mines are all adjacent"" for example) are often unnecessary (meaning you could have solved the puzzle even without it)- - best example for this is the appearance of {5} in a cell - meaning ""five neighbors have mines, all adjacent to each other"". This is silly, as it's the ONLY way to put five neighbor mines in a hex grid!- - but there are other examples of this information just serving nothing help at all. I would expect puzzles with this sort of ""extra information"" that doesn't always appear to be unsolvable without it. This isn't the case here.- You can't easily fine the levels you didn't finish ""perfectly"" if you want to try and redo them.So that's it. I payed 1$ for the game, and it's OK for that price. I wouldn't pay more, nor would I recommend anyone else pay more."
