,Not Recommended,265890,18257573,"Posted: 29 September, 2015",all,CrocoDeath,"First, a warning: the menu screen of the game lists three ""slots"": Slot 1, Slot 2, Slot 3. These are not different parts of the game! I didn't figure it out at first so I finished the game three times without knowing it... Nowhere is stated that the 3 ""slots"" are identical. Bad design!Other than that, well... This game is a lot similar to the absolute Microsoft classic, Minesweeper. Only cooler (and combined with the Japanese game of Kakuro). Main difference is that you almost never have to guess anything (mayber never, but it seems I didn't get all the hints). Which means you solve the puzzles like a math problem, using only logic. it feels great, but it also makes the game really easy.The game is also super short (don't let my playtime fool you, I actually left it running for a whole afternoon while I was out running errands) and contains only 30 puzzles; out of these 30, about 4 are actually challenging — there is more tutorial levels in the game than actual puzzles.And one last thing, the music sounds nice at first but quickly becomes annoying, and you can't deactivate it while in game (again, bad design).Bottom line: I had fun for about 20-30 min and thought the idea behind Hexcells was great, but the game is too easy and way too short for me to recommend it. It would have been free, I would have said go and play it! But I don't think it's worth 2,99 €. It's just like... a draft.I was enticed by the concept though so I'm gonna try Hexcells Plus and see if it is better. See you there."
