76561197998504206,Recommended,265890,13216877,"Posted: 3 December, 2014",all,Red Agliator,"I love the multidirectionality of Hexcells: solving a single cell can affect three lines of cells, as well as the set of surrounding cells. At first, it felt much like a hexagonal version of Minesweeper. When the lines were added, I was reminded of nonograms / paint-by-numbers puzzles. Then, as the puzzles continued, my mind became so occupied with the intersecting logic that I stopped trying to compare it to other games at all.It may be worth skipping this and going directly to Hexcells Plus. First, if you get easily addicted to logic puzzles, Hexcells Plus will keep you thinking for much, much longer. Second, Hexcells Plus' difficulty ramps up slowly and consistently, never adding more than a few techniques at a time. The puzzle difficulty from the original Hexcells increases smoothly at first, but jumps dramatically in the second half. It's a great challenge, but also changes the rhythm of play."
