76561198030660219,Recommended,265890,20276142,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,sortaninja,"80 minutes to get 98%. Recommended for fans of Minesweeper/Picross, at the price that you feel is appropriate for about 1.5 hours of play.I have a fair amount of experience with Minesweeper and Picross-style puzzles, so this felt straightforward and fun. Hexcells ends up using the same logic you'd use for those games. All puzzles are 100% prove-able; there's no forced guessing between multiple spaces. I didn't notice anywhere that I had to string together much ""if this, then this, then this, no that won't work""...no giant cascading logic messes. Comfortable and casual all the way through.Some cautions:-- Unlike some similar games, you aren't marking tiles in a toggle-able way. That is, once you left- or right-click on a tile, it will immediately be shown to be correct or incorrect (which costs you a mistake).-- To me, the default left and right click felt backwards. I restarted the game and swapped them in the pre-game settings window with no problem.-- I played through almost the entire game in a windowed smaller resolution. Puzzle 29 did not fit entirely in the window, and I couldn't find any way to scroll or scale so I could see the whole puzzle. I had to exit back out and start again with non-windowed 1080p, since I figured that would be safe for all puzzles.-- The level select screen does not seem to indicate which puzzles you used a ""mistake"" on, so it looks like it would be annoying to go back and figure that out after the fact. I'd recommend that you immediately retry puzzles if you're aiming for the (very obtainable) perfect achievement, or at least write down which puzzles you'd need to retry later.Don't get me wrong, these cautions are all very minor. I enjoyed this quick game."
